In article <1993Jun8.142630.4113@guvax.acc.georgetown.edu> 
denning@guvax.acc.georgetown.edu writes:

>. . .  Plus the government wants the AT&T phones to use -- 
>shouldn't they be allowed to?  The market-oriented nature of this program 
>appeals to me immensely, much more than the regulated approach
>I suggested we consider in my CACM article.  Another reason for 
>bringing Clipper to market is that it could be too late to do anything 
>at all about the law enforcement needs if telephone security devices such
>as the AT&T device come to market and take off using something like DES.
>[Dorothy Denning]

Once AT&T comes to market with the Clipper devices, what's to stop
Radio Shack from coming to the same market with telephone security
devices "using something like DES"?  Doesn't the whole idea of the
"market-oriented nature" of the Clipper program already represent
an abandonment of law enforcement needs?

					-- Matt Rosenblatt
